{
  "doc_id": "43554",
  "text": "The prevalence of B. procyonis in humans is currently unknown. Moreover, it is likely much higher than what is estimated from the few reported symptomatic patients with neurological disease due to the potential for a larger number of covert and asymptomatic infections to exist undetected [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . This hypothesis is supported by data from serology examinations performed on individuals and in population-based studies (32, 33) (K. R. Kazacos, unpublished data; C. A. Hall, unpublished data) and by blood cell counts of family members used to detect eosinophilia [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] .",
